## <a id="_34gn2lk6qk26"></a>EMMO vs BFO vs TLOs not modeling quantum world

Mark Doerr: Hi Philipp, have you looked into Elementary Multiperspective
Material Ontology \(EMMO\) as an upper level ontology ? for chemists this a very
"natural" ontology since it is based on very solid physics / material
concepts\.\. BFOs origin is Life Science \.\.\. Continuant and Occurrent as root
classes are very counter\-intuitive and far from a physical thinking\.

- Philip: Yes looked at it briefly\.

Mark Doerr:To my impression \(chemist with biochemical and physico\-chemistry
background\) EMMO is way closer to our scientific thinking than what is
conceptionalised in BFO\. I agree that EMMO is still under development, but it
is worth, if NFDI4Chem/Cat/Ing supports this development

- Philip: We thus need documentation and mappings between EMMO and other TLOs
  like BFO that would allow switching between contexts\.

## <a id="_ngp1147hrclr"></a>Normalization of textual definitions / finding duplicate terms over multiple ontologies

Alexander Behr NFDI4Cat: Would a tool help that can list all existing
definitions a class has in several ontologies at once? I programmed such a tool
that might also help in normalizing definition strings of duplicate classes in
ontologies\.

- Philip: We should have easy tools that help us identify definitions that seem
  similar, so we can manually analyze them\. An automatic harmonization would be
  not

suitable atm, because its a too complex topic\.

- Alexander: I totally agree\! The automation of the tool lies in automatically
  gathering similar definitions, human input still is needed to pick the
  �correct� definition\. The image below shows one of the outputs the tool
  generates for the class �mixture� when using 7 semantic artifacts \(can be
  extended if needed to use more semantic artifacts \(ontologies, IUPAC Gold
  book etc\) as one needs\.
- Oliver Koepler \(via chat\): the terminology service Philip mentioned is one
  of the approaches to provide features like this
  [https://terminology\.nfdi4chem\.de](https://terminology.nfdi4chem.de)
- Alexander: The difference to the terminology service would be that all
  duplicate classes of an ontology that are already contained in some other
  ontologie\(s\) can be listed at once and one can obtain the multiple
  definition strings in one place in an ontology file\. This finally allows for
  a kind of straightforward way of listing respective duplicates and finding
  them all at �one place�\. If you need more info, feel free to reach out and/or
  take a look here:
  [https://doi\.org/10\.21203/rs\.3\.rs\-2457909/v1](https://doi.org/10.21203/rs.3.rs-2457909/v1)

## <a id="_dqhsunfiruao"></a>Ontology Metadata standards \- how to judge the quality of an ontology?

- resolves around the question of ontology metadata harmonization
  - e\.g\. should I use skos:prefLabel or rdfs:label, dc:description vs
    iao:definition
  - what metadata must be there \(e\.g\. versionIRI, title, creator, website,
    tracker\)
- links to work already done in this regard
  - Amdouni, E\., Jonquet, C\.: Fair or fairer? an integrated quantitative
    fairness assessment grid for semantic resources and ontologies\. In: MTSR
    2021 \- 15th International Conference on Metadata and Semantics Research,
    p\. \. Springer, Madrid, Spain \(2021\)\.
    doi:10\.13140/RG\.2\.2\.23265\.84321\.[https://hal\-lirmm\.ccsd\.cnrs\.fr/lirmm\-03208544](https://hal-lirmm.ccsd.cnrs.fr/lirmm-03208544)
  - Cox, S\.J\.D\., Gonzalez\-Beltran, A\.N\., Magagna, B\., Marinescu,
    M\.\-C\.: Ten simple rules for making a vocabulary fair\. PLOS Computational
    Biology 17\(6\), 1�15 \(2021\)\.
    doi:[10\.1371/journal\.pcbi\.1009041](https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pcbi.1009041)
  - Xu, F\., Juty, N\.S\., Goble, C\.A\., Jupp, S\., Parkinson, H\.E\., Courtot,
    M\.: Features of a FAIR vocabulary\. In:SWAT4HCLS, pp\. 118�148
    \(2022\)\.[ http://ceur\-ws\.org/Vol\-3127/\#paper\-15](http://ceur-ws.org/Vol-3127/#paper-15)
  - Related to FAIRness of ontologies/vocabularies:

[https://www\.researchsquare\.com/article/rs\-1465079/v1](https://www.researchsquare.com/article/rs-1465079/v1)

- - Ledl, Andreas and Vo�, Jakob\. \(2016\)
    [Describing Knowledge Organization Systems in BARTOC and JSKOS](http://eprints.rclis.org/29366/1/Ledl_Voss_TKE2016_final_version_20160518.pdf)\.
    In: Term Bases and Linguistic Linked Open Data\. Copenhagen, pp\. 168\-178\.
    _\(see Table 1: This harmonization resulted in JSKOS Format for
    Terminologies, see
    _[_https://gbv\.github\.io/jskos/jskos\.html\#concept\-schemes_](https://gbv.github.io/jskos/jskos.html#concept-schemes)_
    \- very broad as it covery all kinds of KOS, from simple categories and
    thesauri to ontologies\)_
- need to discuss what kind of �metrics� should be displayed in terminology
  services for an ontology \(e\.g\. \# of classes w/ only 1 child\)
- related topic: dependency graph of an ontology \- how to annotate and display
  the dependencies \(imported ontology modules/terms\)

## <a id="_hkefye4xarmd"></a>Dependency graph issue

- Linked Open Vocabularies
  \([https://lov\.linkeddata\.es/dataset/lov/](https://lov.linkeddata.es/dataset/lov/)\)
  already covers links and reuse between ontologies\.
  - Unfortunately it does not check, whether the dependency still exists, if the
    PURL resolves or what version of dependency is used \(e\.g\.
    [https://lov\.linkeddata\.es/dataset/lov/vocabs/swc](https://lov.linkeddata.es/dataset/lov/vocabs/swc)
- FAIRsharing \(e\.g\.
  [https://fairsharing\.org/graph/3524](https://fairsharing.org/graph/3524)\)
  seems a more up to date and mighty implementation than LOD
- need to have a dependency graph framework similar to software development
  - e\.g\. going into direction of [https://plow\.pm/](https://plow.pm/)
  - to be able to tell what version of what term/ontology was reused in a
    specific ontology

## <a id="_qghid1n618si"></a>How to proceed operationally within this WG?

- we need to get an overview over all NFDI consortia with respect to
  - what ontologies are used / developed
  - our current pragmatic solution \-> promote to fill out
    [Used Ontologies @ NFDI](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1UAfDKo2gKiaFldEeitMUcO8Gl1Fjyb_r_bp1V4JW0Es)
    - each consortium can add columns to this in which they store information
      not yet covered, such as comments on the quality/reusabilty of the
      respective ontology
      - we can then discuss in how far we can make use of these columns
- make a rolling agenda / overview document for the WG that contains only the
  topics of each meeting and a link to its more specific meeting agenda
  - use this to decide on the topics of the next meetings
  - result:
    [Overview \- WG Ontology Harmonization & Mapping Calls](https://docs.google.com/document/d/14z6kuAdVaiflWUtjqk3LKt-hqg_DeaRCpLY7TFo1PoU/edit)
